00:00:22.874 --> 00:00:24.290
PROFESSOR: Now
generally speaking,

00:00:24.290 --> 00:00:28.226
a proof is going to have
seven characteristics

00:00:28.226 --> 00:00:29.650
that you want to keep in mind.

00:00:33.950 --> 00:00:41.470
Good proofs are correct--
that's obviously important--

00:00:41.470 --> 00:00:46.930
complete-- you've got to
have all the details there.

00:00:46.930 --> 00:00:50.680
All of the key steps
have to be there.

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:54.580
They should be clear so we can
understand what's going on.

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:00.300
Brief is good.

00:01:00.300 --> 00:01:03.630
You don't want to crush
somebody with all the details.

00:01:03.630 --> 00:01:08.570
You want to get to the
key points, and be crisp.

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:10.330
It's really nice
if they're elegant.

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:16.320
Now, that means clever.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:19.397
It's the mathematician's
notion of beauty.

00:01:19.397 --> 00:01:21.730
Like you go to the art museum,
and the artists will say,

00:01:21.730 --> 00:01:24.210
wow, that's a
beautiful painting.

00:01:24.210 --> 00:01:28.160
In mathematics, you say,
wow, that's an elegant proof.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:31.410
It's crisp, clever,
short, to the point.

00:01:31.410 --> 00:01:33.040
And it's really the
highest compliment

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:36.770
you can get from a
mathematician, anyway.

00:01:36.770 --> 00:01:40.882
And there's a lot of
judgment that goes into that.

00:01:40.882 --> 00:01:42.340
Just like in art--
there's judgment

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:44.382
over what is great art.

00:01:44.382 --> 00:01:45.840
The proof should
be well organized.

00:01:50.690 --> 00:01:52.950
For example, use
lemmas the same way

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:54.500
you would use
subroutines in writing

00:01:54.500 --> 00:01:58.400
code-- helps to make it clear.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:00.105
And the proof
should be in order.

00:02:03.150 --> 00:02:05.030
Sometimes you'll see
proofs where things are

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:06.950
done in a haphazard fashion.

00:02:06.950 --> 00:02:09.810
All the pieces are there, but
they're in the wrong order.

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:13.120
Sometimes-- and they teach
this in some high schools--

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:16.790
they teach you to
do proofs backwards.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:18.850
And the classic thing
there is, say you're

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:21.600
trying to prove a equals b.

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:23.530
Well, the proof sometimes
will start with what

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:25.080
you're trying to prove.

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:27.200
And then they'll do
a bunch of steps.

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:29.270
And then you'll end
up with 1 equals 1,

00:02:29.270 --> 00:02:32.900
and you'll write a
check, because you went

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:35.440
from a equals b to 1 equals 1.

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.510
And that's, of course, true.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:40.250
Now, that's not a
good thing to do.

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:45.400
It can be correct if the
implications go this way.

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:49.520
Because really, you're starting
with a fact-- 1 equals 1--

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:51.160
and deriving a equals b.

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:54.000
So if, in fact, the
implications work this way,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:55.720
then your proof is right.

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:58.930
But most people, especially
as you get farther along,

00:02:58.930 --> 00:03:02.470
think about it going
from top to bottom.

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:06.330
So don't use this technique,
because it'll confuse people.

00:03:06.330 --> 00:03:07.940
You're liable to make a mistake.

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:10.790
Just start with 1 equals 1
and work your way from there--

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:13.210
top down for being in order.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:21.090
Now, good proofs are
very much like good code.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:23.750
In fact, one of the reasons we
care so much about teaching you

00:03:23.750 --> 00:03:26.990
how to write a good
proof in computer science

00:03:26.990 --> 00:03:30.180
is so that later on,
you'll be able to prove

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:33.550
that your programs are doing
what you expect-- what they're

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:35.680
supposed to do.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.325
Now, there are many famous
examples where programs did not

00:03:39.325 --> 00:03:40.700
do what they were
supposed to do,

00:03:40.700 --> 00:03:43.340
with disastrous consequences.

00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:48.800
The Airbus A300 was one of the
first commercial jets totally

00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:49.720
operated by software.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:54.140
It could take off, fly, and
land totally by software.

00:03:54.140 --> 00:03:57.600
It was a major advance
in the airline industry.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.110
The only problem
was, that on one

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.140
of the first
flights of the A300,

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:05.240
the software accidentally
opened the rear door just

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:06.580
before landing.

00:04:06.580 --> 00:04:08.940
And the plane
crashed as a result.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:11.740
It was the first plane crash
in commercial history because

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:14.130
of a software bug.

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:17.589
There's a famous radiation
device for cancer patients

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:19.970
called the Therac-25.

00:04:19.970 --> 00:04:23.350
It's famous because it
got into a race condition

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:26.070
occasionally, which
caused the device

00:04:26.070 --> 00:04:29.310
to just slam the patient
with radiation-- so much so,

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:30.700
it killed the patient.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:32.960
And they had multiple examples
of this, and of course,

00:04:32.960 --> 00:04:35.490
a lot of lawsuits afterwards.

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:39.764
How many of you all
remember the 2000 election?

00:04:39.764 --> 00:04:40.430
A few of you do.

00:04:40.430 --> 00:04:44.320
OK, this will probably be the
last class that remembers that.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:47.030
But that's where Al Gore was
going up against George Bush--

00:04:47.030 --> 00:04:49.930
very close election-- all
came down to recounting

00:04:49.930 --> 00:04:52.060
the votes in Florida.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:56.370
But in fact, Al Gore got
negative 16,000 votes

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:59.590
in one county because
of a software bug

00:04:59.590 --> 00:05:02.150
in the electronic
voting booths, which

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:04.501
I think they got rid of a
lot of them in the election

00:05:04.501 --> 00:05:05.000
after that.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.010
Because the software was buggy.

00:05:07.010 --> 00:05:08.840
So poor Al had enough
problem which chads

00:05:08.840 --> 00:05:10.090
and funny business in Florida.

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:12.580
But getting negative
16,000 votes certainly

00:05:12.580 --> 00:05:14.890
didn't help his chances.

00:05:14.890 --> 00:05:17.820
Several years ago, a
single faulty command

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:21.320
in a computer system used by
United and American Airlines

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:24.800
grounded the entire fleets
to both airlines for close

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:26.210
to a day.

00:05:26.210 --> 00:05:28.050
Because they
couldn't do anything.

00:05:28.050 --> 00:05:31.480
They're all run by computer, and
the whole thing was screwed up.

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:33.400
So there's lots more examples.

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:36.790
We run into this issue
all the time at Akamai.

00:05:36.790 --> 00:05:40.760
Akamai is a company started
by MIT folks-- by myself,

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:44.850
and Danny Lewin, and a dozen
undergrads in the late 1990s.

00:05:44.850 --> 00:05:47.720
And we deliver a
lot of the content

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:51.850
you get on the web-- Facebook,
all the search engines.

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:54.790
A lot of the stuff you go
to comes from our servers.

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:56.710
So we've got to be
very careful that we

00:05:56.710 --> 00:05:58.039
don't have software bugs.

00:05:58.039 --> 00:05:58.830
Now, in fact we do.

00:05:58.830 --> 00:06:00.710
And we catch them
every once in awhile.

00:06:00.710 --> 00:06:02.594
But if we got a bad
one, it would bring down

00:06:02.594 --> 00:06:03.760
all the sites you go to you.

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:05.855
You wouldn't be able to
go to those sites anymore.

00:06:05.855 --> 00:06:06.980
And everybody would notice.

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:08.355
It would be sort
of embarrassing.

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:14.680
Now, this really does matter.

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:18.380
And this is going to sound a
little scary, but someday--

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:20.620
probably 30, 20 years
from now, somewhere

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:25.080
in there-- it's possible
that all of us, our lives

00:06:25.080 --> 00:06:29.490
may depend on the software
that some of you write.

00:06:29.490 --> 00:06:32.010
In fact, to bring this
home how scary it is,

00:06:32.010 --> 00:06:34.550
look at the person
sitting next to you.

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:38.750
And imagine that in 25
years, your life depends on

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:40.280
whether their code
does what it's

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:42.820
supposed to do-- little scary.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:51.340
That's why we are
very motivated to help

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:55.660
you learn how to make
rock-solid arguments,

00:06:55.660 --> 00:06:58.290
so you don't have code that
fries one of your classmates

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:03.040
someday, or puts him in
a bad plane situation.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:07.100
Now unfortunately,
writing rock-solid proofs

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:08.910
is a very hard thing to do.

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.380
Even the world's
best mathematicians

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:13.550
mess them up on a regular basis.

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:18.570
In fact, it's estimated that one
third of all published proofs

00:07:18.570 --> 00:07:23.330
have bugs, have flaws, that
render the proof incorrect.

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:28.040
The trouble often arises
because we get lazy.

00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:30.570
We don't write down all the
details or all the steps.

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:32.880
Because, wow, it's clear.

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:35.740
Let's just move on.

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:39.330
Now, this can be OK.

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:42.010
Not such a good practice,
but it dramatically

00:07:42.010 --> 00:07:45.100
increases the chances
of making a mistake.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:46.650
And there's some
very famous examples

00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:48.274
in the math literature
from the world's

00:07:48.274 --> 00:07:50.320
most famous mathematicians.

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:51.837
Gauss-- and we'll
talk about Gauss

00:07:51.837 --> 00:07:53.670
later during the term--
he's one of the most

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:55.420
famous mathematicians ever.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:59.640
He wrote his PhD thesis in 1799.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.440
And it's usually referred to
as the first rigorous proof

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:05.350
of the fundamental
theorem of algebra.

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:08.130
And that says that
every polynomial

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:10.410
has a 0 over the complex
numbers-- something

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:12.325
probably a lot of you
learned in high school.

00:08:12.325 --> 00:08:13.200
You get a polynomial.

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:14.700
You can find roots
of the polynomial

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:17.100
over the complex numbers.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:20.580
But his thesis contains
the following quote,

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:24.730
"If a branch of an algebraic
curve enters a bounded region,

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:27.870
it must necessarily leave again.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:31.480
Nobody, to my knowledge,
has ever doubted this fact."

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:34.679
Warning signs-- buzzers-- should
be going off in your brain.

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:37.090
"But if anybody desires it,
then on another occasion,

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:41.100
I intend to give a demonstration
which will leave no doubt."

00:08:41.100 --> 00:08:44.620
So he's using something
that he believes to be true.

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:48.420
He sort of thinks it's clear,
that everybody knows it.

00:08:48.420 --> 00:08:49.530
But he writes this down.

00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:50.946
And when you're
writing that down,

00:08:50.946 --> 00:08:52.730
you know there's a problem.

00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:54.700
And in fact, there's
another Fields medalist--

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:57.800
we talked about Fields medals
last week-- Stephen Smale

00:08:57.800 --> 00:09:02.650
writes that this was an immense
gap in the proof that was not

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:06.500
filled until 1920-- more
than 100 years later.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:08.310
So Gauss never could
give the proof,

00:09:08.310 --> 00:09:11.870
and nobody did for
over a century more.

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:14.830
Remember the Poincare
conjecture from last week?

00:09:14.830 --> 00:09:17.210
We had Colbert
talking about that.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:22.440
In 1900, Poincare claimed
it was a simple fact.

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:25.790
Four years later, he
decided it wasn't so simple,

00:09:25.790 --> 00:09:28.600
and he demoted his claim to
the status of a conjecture.

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:32.240
And of course, this became the
famous Poincare conjecture,

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:35.480
which took another
century to solve.

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.380
So when you think you
see yourself doing this,

00:09:38.380 --> 00:09:41.714
famous mathematicians do it
too, and it catches them.

00:09:41.714 --> 00:09:43.130
So you want to not
try to do that.

00:09:43.130 --> 00:09:46.260
Now, in fact, just to
really bring home the point,

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:49.940
we've made a top 10
list of proof techniques

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.330
you should not use in 6.042.

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:54.624
So everybody go to
the handout here.

00:09:54.624 --> 00:09:56.540
In fact, there's lot of
them on the back, too,

00:09:56.540 --> 00:09:58.730
but on the front page,
there's the top 10.

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.220
So we're going to
go through these.

00:10:01.220 --> 00:10:02.910
These are the ones
we've most observed

00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:05.020
in 6.042 over the years.

00:10:05.020 --> 00:10:09.270
Number 10-- proof by
throwing in the kitchen sink.

00:10:09.270 --> 00:10:11.930
The author writes down every
theorem known to mankind,

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:14.445
and then adds a few
more for good measure.

00:10:14.445 --> 00:10:16.820
Now, this is good, because
when you're questioned later--

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:19.780
you're trying to get a
better score on your exam--

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:22.810
you say, look, the proof
contains all the key facts.

00:10:22.810 --> 00:10:25.010
They're all here.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:26.030
And so that does help.

00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:28.030
You get extra credit if
all the facts are there.

00:10:28.030 --> 00:10:31.267
We are literally seen students
copy over their crib sheet,

00:10:31.267 --> 00:10:33.350
if they got enough time,
for a problem they're not

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:37.250
knowing how to solve, just to
get all of the facts in there.

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:40.590
Number nine-- proof by example--
the author gives the case n

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:42.290
equals 2 and
suggests it contains

00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:44.166
most of the ideas of
the general proof.

00:10:44.166 --> 00:10:45.540
In fact, a student
before a class

00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:47.690
was telling me on one of
the homework problems,

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:50.410
he talked about it to
his non-math friends,

00:10:50.410 --> 00:10:54.220
and they gave examples,
not the proof.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:57.210
Number eight-- proof by
vigorous hand-waving-- one

00:10:57.210 --> 00:10:59.440
of my favorites-- I get
up here and wave my hands.

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:00.575
And it must be true.

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:06.890
Number seven-- proof by
cumbersome notation--

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:09.080
here the reader gets
hopelessly confused,

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:11.060
gives up, and says OK.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:13.130
In fact, I once
had a grad student,

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:15.740
and we called him the
encryptor, because he

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:19.900
could take the simplest proof
and so encrypt it in notation

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:23.170
and God knows what, you could
never understand the proof

00:11:23.170 --> 00:11:25.990
and figure out if it was
really right or wrong.

00:11:25.990 --> 00:11:29.520
That goes well with number
six-- proof by exhaustion--

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:31.850
so does throwing in
the kitchen sink.

00:11:31.850 --> 00:11:33.870
Number five--
proof by omission--

00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:37.680
you will see that a lot,
also by faculty-- "The reader

00:11:37.680 --> 00:11:40.300
may easily supply the details.

00:11:40.300 --> 00:11:43.150
The other cases are
analogous-- trivial."

00:11:43.150 --> 00:11:44.400
Experts use that all the time.

00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:46.340
You can find a lot
of my papers online.

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:48.840
"The proof is
trivial"-- very bad.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:51.920
Every once in a while, it
turned out not to be so trivial.

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:55.170
Number four-- proof by
picture-- we've seen those,

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.000
saw one on Tuesday.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.230
Number three-- proof by
vehement assertion-- sort

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:01.800
of like the hand-waving.

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:03.780
The more forceful you
are in your argument,

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:06.400
the higher you raise your
voice, the more intimidating

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:10.160
you become, doesn't
make it more true.

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:14.350
Number two-- proof by appeal
to intuition-- you say,

00:12:14.350 --> 00:12:17.230
"any moron knows that."

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:20.480
Well, you're sort of
reluctant to now question it.

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:23.430
And then number one-- proof by
reference to eminent authority.

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:26.480
I saw Fermat on the elevator
and he said he had a proof.

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:28.330
I don't think so.

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:31.420
Fermat's been dead
for over 300 years.

00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:34.840
And he was not so reliable
in the first place.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.940
In fact, he has one of
the most famous assertions

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:41.860
that turned into a conjecture,
called Fermat's last theorem.

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:44.425
And it was not really a
theorem by the time he died.

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:49.860
How many people have heard
of Fermat's last theorem?

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:51.010
Raise your hand.

00:12:51.010 --> 00:12:52.920
Yeah, pretty famous.

00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:56.935
It's the one theorem he proved
that actually, he didn't prove.

00:12:56.935 --> 00:12:59.850
It says, for all
n bigger than 2,

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:08.220
there does not exist an x, y,
and z in the natural numbers

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:12.040
plus the positive natural
numbers such that x to the n

00:13:12.040 --> 00:13:15.540
plus y to the n
equals z to the n.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:18.370
Now of course, for
n equals 2, that's

00:13:18.370 --> 00:13:19.580
just the Pythagorean theorem.

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:22.180
You can find three,
four, and five, when

00:13:22.180 --> 00:13:24.860
you square them satisfy that.

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:28.970
But it says this does not
work for any higher value,

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:31.360
any higher power, than 2.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:37.030
Now in 1637, Fermat wrote
in the margin of a block

00:13:37.030 --> 00:13:39.410
that he had discovered
a proof of this result,

00:13:39.410 --> 00:13:42.510
but the proof was too
long to fit in the margin.

00:13:42.510 --> 00:13:45.870
And so he wasn't going to
supply the details there.

00:13:45.870 --> 00:13:47.730
And he never did
supply the details.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:52.750
And it took 350 years and
100s and 100s of pages.

00:13:52.750 --> 00:13:55.860
A fellow named Andrew
Wiles-- took him personally

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:56.710
over 10 years.

00:13:56.710 --> 00:13:58.620
He more or less locked
himself in his room

00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:01.360
for 10 years, produced
100s of pages,

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:04.350
and he finally did prove
Fermat's Last Theorem.

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.520
So Fermat was right
about one thing--

00:14:06.520 --> 00:14:08.224
it would not fit in the margin.

00:14:08.224 --> 00:14:09.640
At least, there's
no proof that we

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:12.990
know of that would fit
in the margin of a book.

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:16.480
Any questions on
proof technique?

