00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:16.990
There is no sequence
of legal moves--

00:21:16.990 --> 00:21:26.680
diagonal moves makes this a
lot easier-- to invert g and h

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:37.530
and also return all the other
letters to their original order

00:21:37.530 --> 00:21:38.106
or position.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:53.790
Now, to prove this,
we're going to use

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:56.530
what's called an invariant.

00:21:56.530 --> 00:21:58.910
It's a very powerful
and commonly used

00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:02.470
concept in computer science,
very closely tied to induction,

00:22:02.470 --> 00:22:04.500
as we'll see.

00:22:04.500 --> 00:22:07.800
In order to show that
your system can never

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:11.580
reach a particular
special state,

00:22:11.580 --> 00:22:13.900
it is sufficient to show
there's some property called

00:22:13.900 --> 00:22:17.880
the invariant that holds
at the initial state,

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:21.540
and that is preserved
by every legal move,

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:26.770
and is not present-- does not
hold-- in that special state.

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:29.230
The idea is, if you get
this magic property called

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:31.540
the invariant and it
holds at the start,

00:22:31.540 --> 00:22:34.150
and it holds across
every step, then

00:22:34.150 --> 00:22:36.640
the only states
you can reach have

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:39.450
to have to have the
property, be invariant.

00:22:39.450 --> 00:22:42.850
And if the special state
doesn't have that property,

00:22:42.850 --> 00:22:45.060
you can't reach it.

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:47.970
All right, so there
is going to be

00:22:47.970 --> 00:22:50.130
some property we're going
to look for that held

00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:53.110
at the beginning here-- and
the beginning had this set

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:59.420
up-- that holds, is
preserved, by every move,

00:22:59.420 --> 00:23:03.800
every legal move, but does
not hold in this state.

00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:06.527
And therefore, you can never
reach this state legally.

00:23:06.527 --> 00:23:07.360
So they were doomed.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:12.710
So we've got to figure
out what that property is.

00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:17.730
And that's always the
trick in analyzing

00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:19.790
systems or
algorithms-- is what's

00:23:19.790 --> 00:23:22.930
that key property, the
invariant property?

00:23:22.930 --> 00:23:24.680
So to figure out the
invariant, we sort of

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:27.700
have to look at what
happens during a move

00:23:27.700 --> 00:23:30.080
in this system-- a transition.

00:23:30.080 --> 00:23:33.130
Well, there's two
kinds of moves.

00:23:33.130 --> 00:23:34.080
There's a row move.

00:23:37.860 --> 00:23:45.590
And an example of a
row move is you might

00:23:45.590 --> 00:23:53.560
have a, b, c, d, g, e, f, h.

00:23:53.560 --> 00:23:57.810
And I'm going to move the g
its row to the blank square.

00:23:57.810 --> 00:23:59.812
So it would become this state.

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:07.720
So g moves rightward
into the blank,

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:11.020
and the rest stays the same.

00:24:11.020 --> 00:24:16.150
Now, when I make a row
move, did the relative order

00:24:16.150 --> 00:24:18.135
of the items change?

00:24:21.060 --> 00:24:21.624
No.

00:24:21.624 --> 00:24:23.040
Of course, to be
precise, I better

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:27.280
define what relative order
means, or the natural order.

00:24:27.280 --> 00:24:39.210
So by the natural order, I mean
this ordering-- 1, 2 3, 4, 5,

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:42.100
6, 7, 8, 9.

00:24:42.100 --> 00:24:47.070
So if I look at the order
here, g moved from 5 to 6,

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:49.090
but didn't change
order with respect

00:24:49.090 --> 00:24:50.150
to any of the other guys.

00:24:52.874 --> 00:24:54.040
Let's state that as a lemma.

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:05.490
Because that'll be very useful.

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:21.920
Lemma 1-- a row move
does not change the order

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:24.940
of the items or the letters.

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:33.590
Proof-- well, it's obvious.

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:41.640
No, you can't let me get
away with that, right?

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:44.490
Because I'm not to let you get
away with that on homework.

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:47.120
That's not so good.

00:25:47.120 --> 00:25:51.140
So we've got to be a little
more careful in the proof here.

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:54.580
Otherwise, we just head
down the path to trouble.

00:25:54.580 --> 00:25:57.520
So let's sort of specify,
what does a row move

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:03.450
mean-- just get a little bit
of math and specification

00:26:03.450 --> 00:26:05.140
around it.

00:26:05.140 --> 00:26:13.720
Well, in a row move,
we move an item--

00:26:13.720 --> 00:26:23.680
a letter-- from some
cell i, whatever

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:30.170
i-- it could be anything 1
to 9-- into an adjacent cell.

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:40.720
What are the possibilities
for the adjacent cell?

00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:50.120
Plus or minus 1, yeah, into
cell i minus 1 or i plus 1.

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:51.085
Nothing else moves.

00:26:59.230 --> 00:27:05.920
Hence, the order of
the items is preserved.

00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:19.600
Because if you're going
with i to i plus 1,

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:23.450
everything else is in i minus
1 or less, i plus 2 or more.

00:27:23.450 --> 00:27:25.790
Relative order does not
change in this case.

00:27:28.450 --> 00:27:30.570
And I'll claim that's enough.

00:27:30.570 --> 00:27:32.910
You know that I've thought
about it a little bit.

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:35.820
I've really quantified that i
goes to i minus 1 or i plus 1.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:37.460
Nothing else moves.

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:38.780
Therefore, we're done.

00:27:38.780 --> 00:27:40.920
Now, I could've added
some more sentences here,

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:42.400
like I talked about.

00:27:42.400 --> 00:27:46.050
But this is probably enough
in this case, for this guy.

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:53.400
So in fact, if we
only had row moves,

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:54.650
there's not much that happens.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.184
The order never
changes with row moves.

00:27:57.184 --> 00:27:58.100
So we never get there.

00:27:58.100 --> 00:27:59.683
But column moves are
more interesting.

00:28:06.320 --> 00:28:19.042
So as an example of a column
move, a, b, c, d, f, h, e,

00:28:19.042 --> 00:28:23.220
g-- say I move the g up.

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:33.000
Then I would get this one--
a, b, c, d, f, g-- because g

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:35.420
moved up-- h, e.

00:28:35.420 --> 00:28:36.550
So g went to there.

00:28:40.240 --> 00:28:43.690
Did the ordering
change for this move?

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:46.300
Yeah.

00:28:46.300 --> 00:28:48.450
How so?

00:28:48.450 --> 00:28:49.570
What things changed order?

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:51.630
Which pairs of
letters changed order?

00:28:54.576 --> 00:28:56.540
AUDIENCE: G changed [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:56.540 --> 00:29:00.450
PROFESSOR: G changed by three--
moved three in the order.

00:29:00.450 --> 00:29:04.837
And what letters did it
change relative order with?

00:29:04.837 --> 00:29:07.831
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:29:07.831 --> 00:29:09.830
AUDIENCE: The two preceding it.

00:29:09.830 --> 00:29:11.800
PROFESSOR: Yeah, the
two preceding it.

00:29:11.800 --> 00:29:14.790
g used to be after h and e.

00:29:14.790 --> 00:29:18.070
Now it's before h and e.

00:29:18.070 --> 00:29:21.750
All right, so it changed
relative order with two items.

00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:23.300
It changed its
position by three.

00:29:23.300 --> 00:29:25.100
It moved up three
in the ordering.

00:29:25.100 --> 00:29:28.020
And so it changed order
with the two in between.

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:30.630
Let's look at another one.

00:29:30.630 --> 00:29:32.760
Because we're really
doing these examples

00:29:32.760 --> 00:29:35.190
to hunt for an
invariant, is what

00:29:35.190 --> 00:29:37.530
we're trying to do
here-- something

00:29:37.530 --> 00:29:41.710
that will let us prove we can
never get to the desired state.

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:43.750
Let's look at this one.

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:54.050
a, b, c, d, g, h,
e, f goes to-- I'm

00:29:54.050 --> 00:30:05.680
going to move b down this
time-- a, c, d, b, g, h, e, f.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:09.225
So b moves down.

00:30:09.225 --> 00:30:12.470
The relative order changes.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:15.120
Which pairs got changed
in the relative order?

00:30:19.870 --> 00:30:20.820
AUDIENCE: b.

00:30:20.820 --> 00:30:22.264
PROFESSOR: b changed with--

00:30:22.264 --> 00:30:23.430
AUDIENCE: c and [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:23.430 --> 00:30:27.070
PROFESSOR: c and d.

00:30:27.070 --> 00:30:30.380
b used to be before c and
d. when it moves down here,

00:30:30.380 --> 00:30:34.160
it goes after c and d.

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:37.580
Any guess about what
