00:30:40.544 --> 00:30:41.460
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:44.192
PROFESSOR: Change the order of--

00:30:44.192 --> 00:30:45.108
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:50.030 --> 00:30:52.770
PROFESSOR: Good,
so a column move

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:55.971
changes the order of a
guy with the previous two

00:30:55.971 --> 00:30:58.470
or the next two, which means
the relative order of two pairs

00:30:58.470 --> 00:30:59.887
change.

00:30:59.887 --> 00:31:01.220
So let's take that as Lemma Two.

00:31:04.750 --> 00:31:06.660
When we say don't
do proof by example,

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:09.220
we don't mean
don't try examples.

00:31:09.220 --> 00:31:11.300
Because by trying
examples, you find out

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:13.370
what you're trying to prove.

00:31:13.370 --> 00:31:15.680
So that's good to do.

00:31:15.680 --> 00:31:39.600
A column move changes the
relative order of precisely two

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:40.670
pairs of items.

00:31:46.860 --> 00:31:47.750
So let's prove that.

00:31:53.130 --> 00:32:12.010
In a column move, we move
an item in cell i for some i

00:32:12.010 --> 00:32:22.642
to a blank spot in cell what?

00:32:22.642 --> 00:32:24.580
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:24.580 --> 00:32:27.334
PROFESSOR: i minus
3 or i plus 3?

00:32:27.334 --> 00:32:28.250
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:31.860 --> 00:32:35.590
PROFESSOR: OK, and just to
see that, let's draw out

00:32:35.590 --> 00:32:36.340
the natural order.

00:32:36.340 --> 00:32:40.890
I've got 1 2, 3,
4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9.

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:46.690
Column moves could be here--
1 to 4, and 4 to 1, 2 and 5,

00:32:46.690 --> 00:32:51.880
3 and 6, 4 and 7,
5 and 8, 6 and 9.

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:55.810
All 12 possible column
moves, this works for.

00:32:55.810 --> 00:32:57.310
They're always separated by 3.

00:33:00.170 --> 00:33:17.080
And when an item
moves three positions,

00:33:17.080 --> 00:33:19.540
it changes relative order
with two other items.

00:33:27.360 --> 00:33:29.950
And you can even write
down what they are.

00:33:29.950 --> 00:33:36.942
It's i minus 1, i minus
2, or i plus 1, i plus 2.

00:33:36.942 --> 00:33:38.650
Those are the guys it
changes order with.

00:33:42.559 --> 00:33:44.100
All right, we've
got two lemmas here.

00:33:44.100 --> 00:33:46.380
That one's done now.

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:49.100
In a row move, order
does not change.

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:55.070
In a column move, two pairs
of letters get flipped.

00:33:55.070 --> 00:33:58.240
That's all you can do
with this puzzle now.

00:33:58.240 --> 00:34:01.950
So can anybody
think of something

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:04.890
we can work with to get an
invariant here-- something

00:34:04.890 --> 00:34:06.460
that won't change?

00:34:06.460 --> 00:34:07.710
What we should be focusing on?

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:09.070
Yeah.

00:34:09.070 --> 00:34:12.990
AUDIENCE: You can only switch
two pairs of items at a time.

00:34:12.990 --> 00:34:18.380
So if you don't have an
even number [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:18.380 --> 00:34:20.850
switch [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:20.850 --> 00:34:22.199
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's good.

00:34:22.199 --> 00:34:24.139
So really, to focus
in on there is,

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:27.600
if you have an even number
of things out of order

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:30.620
to start, you're going to
have an even number forever,

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:32.860
because you can only
change two at a time.

00:34:32.860 --> 00:34:33.820
That's a great idea.

00:34:33.820 --> 00:34:38.159
Let's really specify that
now, and define that.

00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:52.420
A pair of letters or items,
call them L1 and L2--

00:34:52.420 --> 00:35:12.520
they form an inversion, also
known as an inverted pair,

00:35:12.520 --> 00:35:24.160
if L1 precedes L2
in the alphabet,

00:35:24.160 --> 00:35:27.140
but L1 appears after
L2 in the puzzle.

00:35:38.170 --> 00:35:41.470
All right, so that
is an inversion.

00:35:41.470 --> 00:35:43.960
So for example, let's
see how many inversions

00:35:43.960 --> 00:35:45.060
do we have in this case?

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:57.850
We've got a, b,
c, f, d, g, e, h.

00:35:57.850 --> 00:36:00.550
How many inversions are there
in that state of the puzzle?

00:36:12.740 --> 00:36:14.070
Yeah?

00:36:14.070 --> 00:36:14.950
AUDIENCE: Three.

00:36:14.950 --> 00:36:15.908
PROFESSOR: Three, good.

00:36:15.908 --> 00:36:17.866
And what are they?

00:36:17.866 --> 00:36:20.130
AUDIENCE: d is after f.

00:36:20.130 --> 00:36:22.040
PROFESSOR: Yeah, d,
f is an inversion.

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:29.600
e, f is an inversion.

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:31.480
And what's the last one?

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:32.250
AUDIENCE: e, g.

00:36:32.250 --> 00:36:34.320
PROFESSOR: e, g is an inversion.

00:36:34.320 --> 00:36:37.430
Yes, so the answer is
there's three inversions

00:36:37.430 --> 00:36:39.680
in this puzzle.

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:41.960
And if I keep doing
row and column

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:45.200
moves to this, what do
I know about the parity

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:47.746
of the number of inversions?

00:36:47.746 --> 00:36:50.430
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:54.040
PROFESSOR: Will always be odd--
that's sort of interesting.

00:36:54.040 --> 00:37:02.180
OK, now, how many inverted pairs
are there in the start state

00:37:02.180 --> 00:37:05.100
way back over here?

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:08.440
How many inverted pairs here?

00:37:08.440 --> 00:37:09.215
One inversion.

00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:17.986
How many inversions here?

00:37:17.986 --> 00:37:18.485
Zero.

00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:27.350
All right, and can you see where
we're going to head here now?

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:32.080
If I started with
one, that's odd.

00:37:32.080 --> 00:37:34.190
And every time I do a
row move or column move,

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:35.750
it's going to stay odd.

00:37:35.750 --> 00:37:38.930
And I can never get here.

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:41.190
Is that clear what
we're trying to do?

00:37:41.190 --> 00:37:42.380
So let's keep doing it.

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:47.350
Let's go over here.

00:37:59.110 --> 00:38:02.510
All right, so now we'll
use Lemma One and Lemma Two

00:38:02.510 --> 00:38:05.820
create this notion that we only
change the number of inversions

00:38:05.820 --> 00:38:07.883
by an even number.

00:38:07.883 --> 00:38:28.130
And Lemma Three-- during a
move, the number of inversions

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:42.500
can only increase by
two, decrease by two,

00:38:42.500 --> 00:38:44.230
or stay the same.

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:51.210
And this proof is pretty easy.

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:53.060
There's a couple of cases.

00:38:56.910 --> 00:39:01.250
In a row move, what happens?

00:39:01.250 --> 00:39:04.380
How does the number
of inversions

00:39:04.380 --> 00:39:05.629
change in a row move?

00:39:05.629 --> 00:39:06.670
AUDIENCE: Stays the same.

00:39:06.670 --> 00:39:09.770
PROFESSOR: Stays the
same-- no changes--

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:11.090
and that's by Lemma One.

00:39:17.910 --> 00:39:20.725
Now, in a column move,
there's three cases.

00:39:26.330 --> 00:39:29.432
But we know two pairs
change order-- that we know.

00:39:29.432 --> 00:39:30.140
That's Lemma Two.

00:39:34.117 --> 00:39:35.700
All right, by Lemma
Two, we know that.

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:42.857
But the three cases are-- let
me start on the next board.

00:40:00.780 --> 00:40:07.850
So Case A is that both
of the inverted pairs

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:14.030
were in order originally,
before the column move.

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:17.720
What happens to the number
of inversions in this case,

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:20.588
as a result of the column move?

00:40:20.588 --> 00:40:21.777
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:21.777 --> 00:40:22.860
PROFESSOR: Goes up by two.

00:40:25.700 --> 00:40:31.080
Case B is that both
pairs were inverted

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:34.250
before I made the column move.

00:40:34.250 --> 00:40:37.994
What happens to the number
of inversions in that case?

00:40:37.994 --> 00:40:39.179
AUDIENCE: Decreases by two.

00:40:39.179 --> 00:40:41.220
PROFESSOR: Decreases by
two-- they were in order,

00:40:41.220 --> 00:40:42.700
so they were inverted.

00:40:42.700 --> 00:40:46.010
Now when I flop them,
they become in order.

00:40:46.010 --> 00:40:48.470
So inversions drops by two.

00:40:48.470 --> 00:40:51.650
And Case C is
there's one of each.

00:40:51.650 --> 00:40:53.010
One of the pairs was inverted.

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:58.870
The other wasn't.

00:40:58.870 --> 00:41:02.040
What happens to the number
of inversions in that case?

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:03.030
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:03.030 --> 00:41:04.321
PROFESSOR: Yes, stays the same.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:11.339
All right, and we're done.

00:41:11.339 --> 00:41:13.880
That's what the lemma says-- I
can go up by two, down by two,

00:41:13.880 --> 00:41:16.990
or stay the same.

00:41:16.990 --> 00:41:21.820
All right, now a simple
corollary of this

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:26.200
is that during a move, the
parity-- i.e. even or odd

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:29.750
of the number of
inversions stays the same.

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:30.870
It can't change at all.

00:41:39.450 --> 00:41:45.840
During a move, the parity--
and the parity means even, odd.

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:50.590
Sometimes it's called
0, 1, but the evenness

00:41:50.590 --> 00:42:01.460
and the oddness of the number
of inversions does not change.

00:42:08.456 --> 00:42:11.420
AUDIENCE: Instead of two pairs
you mean one pair, right?

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:12.902
PROFESSOR: Where?

00:42:12.902 --> 00:42:15.760
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] pairs.

00:42:15.760 --> 00:42:18.530
PROFESSOR: Oops, I mean
one pair's inverted,

00:42:18.530 --> 00:42:19.984
one pair's not.

00:42:19.984 --> 00:42:20.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:27.860
PROFESSOR: No, I mean two pairs
change order in a column move.

00:42:27.860 --> 00:42:30.600
Let's go back and look at that.

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:31.980
So I'm doing a column move.

00:42:31.980 --> 00:42:36.490
For example, g goes up.

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:38.470
g, h changes order.

00:42:38.470 --> 00:42:41.320
g, e changes order.

00:42:41.320 --> 00:42:43.610
g changes order
with these two guys,

00:42:43.610 --> 00:42:47.830
so there's two pairs
that got flipped.

00:42:47.830 --> 00:42:51.230
So in a column move, two
pairs reverse their order.

00:42:51.230 --> 00:42:53.240
If they were in order,
they become inverted.

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:56.792
If they were inverted,
they become in order.

00:42:56.792 --> 00:42:57.625
Any other questions?

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:01.350
Yeah.

00:43:01.350 --> 00:43:03.270
AUDIENCE: So we're saying
that letters can be

00:43:03.270 --> 00:43:06.160
numbers in more than one pair?

00:43:06.160 --> 00:43:08.470
PROFESSOR: Yes, a letter
can be in-- a letter

00:43:08.470 --> 00:43:13.250
is in seven pairs, because
there's seven other letters.

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:19.000
And in fact, we're looking
at a space of 8 times 7

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:22.195
divided by 2-- 28
pairs of letters.

00:43:22.195 --> 00:43:26.237
So there could be 28 inversions
if they're all out of order.

00:43:26.237 --> 00:43:27.070
Any other questions?

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:32.230
OK, well, we're getting there.

00:43:32.230 --> 00:43:32.980
We're almost done.

00:43:32.980 --> 00:43:35.720
I've got to prove this
corollary that during a move,

00:43:35.720 --> 00:43:38.210
the evenness or oddness of
the number of inversions

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:38.920
does not change.

00:43:42.450 --> 00:43:46.410
And that's because adding or
subtracting 2 from a number

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:48.440
does not change its parity.

00:43:48.440 --> 00:43:51.780
It stays odd or stays even.

00:43:51.780 --> 00:44:03.450
So adding or subtracting 2
does not change the parity.

00:44:11.987 --> 00:44:14.070
All right, now we're ready
to state the invariant.

00:44:24.310 --> 00:44:27.930
Anybody tell me what the
invariant is going to be?

00:44:27.930 --> 00:44:31.805
What's the invariant going
to be in this system?

00:44:31.805 --> 00:44:33.140
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:33.140 --> 00:44:37.630
PROFESSOR: Yeah, the parity
of the number of inversions

00:44:37.630 --> 00:44:41.650
is odd, because it
starts that way.

00:44:41.650 --> 00:44:42.960
It's preserved.

00:44:42.960 --> 00:44:45.720
And it won't hold in
the desired end state

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:47.182
that we're looking at.

00:44:47.182 --> 00:44:48.515
So we can state that as follows.

00:44:55.240 --> 00:45:05.810
In every state or
configuration reachable

00:45:05.810 --> 00:45:13.530
from the start
state, which is a,

00:45:13.530 --> 00:45:21.160
b, c, d, e, f, h, g--
which are out of order--

00:45:21.160 --> 00:45:30.690
the parity of the number
of inversions is odd.

00:45:35.220 --> 00:45:38.440
And the proof will
be by induction.

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:40.750
And invariant proofs
are always by induction.

00:45:46.790 --> 00:45:50.100
And the inductive
hypothesis-- and this

00:45:50.100 --> 00:45:52.270
is very typical in
a proof by using

00:45:52.270 --> 00:46:11.910
invariants-- is, so P of n is
after any sequence of n moves

00:46:11.910 --> 00:46:17.260
from the start state-- in
fact, just the rest of this

00:46:17.260 --> 00:46:18.020
is what it is.

00:46:25.700 --> 00:46:29.280
All right, so our inductive
hypothesis is P of n,

00:46:29.280 --> 00:46:33.510
after any sequence of n moves--
so n is the number of moves

00:46:33.510 --> 00:46:37.510
you took to get there--
from the start state,

00:46:37.510 --> 00:46:41.550
the parity of the number
of inversions is odd.

00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:44.180
That is the
inductive hypothesis.

00:46:44.180 --> 00:46:45.680
This is the invariant.

00:46:45.680 --> 00:46:47.380
And they become
one and the same.

00:46:47.380 --> 00:46:50.960
And the parameter n is the
number of moves you've taken.

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:53.625
And that's how you set up
a proof using an invariant.

00:46:53.625 --> 00:46:55.774
It always looks just like this.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:19.220
OK, so we're doing a
proof by induction.

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:22.720
We've got the
inductive hypothesis.

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:24.837
What's the next step?

00:47:24.837 --> 00:47:25.670
AUDIENCE: Base case.

00:47:25.670 --> 00:47:26.545
PROFESSOR: Base case.

00:47:32.456 --> 00:47:34.830
And in these circumstances,
where the proof by invariant,

00:47:34.830 --> 00:47:37.590
the base case is always 0.

00:47:37.590 --> 00:47:40.020
We haven't made any moves yet.

00:47:40.020 --> 00:47:41.860
Now in this case, if
we haven't made moves,

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:48.870
the number of inversions in
the start state now is 1.

00:47:48.870 --> 00:47:55.380
That means the parity is
odd, and the hypothesis

00:47:55.380 --> 00:47:56.230
is satisfied.

00:47:56.230 --> 00:48:00.650
P of 0 is true, because in
any sequence of zero moves,

00:48:00.650 --> 00:48:02.092
after this-- i.e.

00:48:02.092 --> 00:48:03.800
in this state-- you've
got one inversion.

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:06.602
That's odd.

00:48:06.602 --> 00:48:08.815
The last step is
the inductive step.

00:48:16.690 --> 00:48:22.510
And here we need to show for
any n bigger or equal to 0,

00:48:22.510 --> 00:48:29.980
we need to show P of n implies
p of n plus 1 is true--

00:48:29.980 --> 00:48:32.990
the standard thing.

00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:35.770
So let's look at P n plus 1.

00:48:35.770 --> 00:48:38.260
That's talking
about where we are

00:48:38.260 --> 00:48:42.550
after a sequence of n plus
1 moves in the puzzle,

00:48:42.550 --> 00:48:45.610
from the start state.

00:48:45.610 --> 00:48:58.790
So let's consider any
sequence of n plus 1 moves.

00:48:58.790 --> 00:49:00.545
And call these
moves-- label them

00:49:00.545 --> 00:49:05.394
by M1 all the way to M n plus 1.

00:49:05.394 --> 00:49:06.560
Those are the moves we made.

00:49:09.080 --> 00:49:13.680
Now, by the inductive
hypothesis, because of P n,

00:49:13.680 --> 00:49:17.720
we know that after the first n
moves, the parity is still odd.

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:20.170
That's what P n says.

00:49:20.170 --> 00:49:20.980
That's P n.

00:49:20.980 --> 00:49:24.774
After any sequence
of n moves from here,

00:49:24.774 --> 00:49:26.690
the parity of the number
of inversions is odd.

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:31.460
So we could say by the
inductive hypothesis,

00:49:31.460 --> 00:49:48.450
or we could say by P n, we know
that the parity after moves

00:49:48.450 --> 00:49:54.340
M1 out to M n is odd.

00:50:00.130 --> 00:50:05.240
Now, by Corollary One-- do
we still have Corollary One?

00:50:05.240 --> 00:50:06.724
[INAUDIBLE]

00:50:06.724 --> 00:50:07.640
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:07.640 --> 00:50:10.140
PROFESSOR: [INAUDIBLE], yeah,
good, we've got Corollary One.

00:50:10.140 --> 00:50:14.650
During any move, the
parity doesn't change.

00:50:14.650 --> 00:50:19.190
That says from after the nth
move to after the n plus 1st

00:50:19.190 --> 00:50:22.141
move-- one extra move--
doesn't change the parity.

00:50:22.141 --> 00:50:22.890
So it's still odd.

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:50.080
So next, by Corollary
One, we know

00:50:50.080 --> 00:50:59.010
that the parity of the
number of inversions

00:50:59.010 --> 00:51:01.840
does not change
during M n plus 1.

00:51:14.744 --> 00:51:25.710
Therefore, this implies that
the parity after all n plus 1

00:51:25.710 --> 00:51:35.340
moves-- these guys-- is odd.

00:51:35.340 --> 00:51:37.180
It started odd.

00:51:37.180 --> 00:51:39.150
It stayed odd after the first n.

00:51:39.150 --> 00:51:41.580
It stayed odd during
the n plus 1st.

00:51:41.580 --> 00:51:43.940
So it's odd.

00:51:43.940 --> 00:51:48.780
And that's exactly the
statement of P n plus 1.

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:50.740
So we've completed
the induction.

00:51:50.740 --> 00:51:53.247
We've shown that P n
implies P n plus 1.

00:51:56.450 --> 00:52:01.241
All right, so now, any
questions so far on this?

00:52:01.241 --> 00:52:01.989
Yeah.

00:52:01.989 --> 00:52:03.947
AUDIENCE: What's the
difference between a lemma

00:52:03.947 --> 00:52:05.300
and a corollary?

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:07.440
PROFESSOR: Really, there's
not a lot of difference.

00:52:07.440 --> 00:52:09.450
Corollary usually
is something that's

00:52:09.450 --> 00:52:12.870
a simple consequence
of something else.

00:52:12.870 --> 00:52:16.734
And the corollary had
a pretty short proof.

00:52:16.734 --> 00:52:19.150
Usually when you see corollary,
that's not a 10-page proof

00:52:19.150 --> 00:52:19.770
there.

00:52:19.770 --> 00:52:22.410
A lemma is something
that you're going

00:52:22.410 --> 00:52:25.010
to use as a tool for
a bigger thing, often

00:52:25.010 --> 00:52:27.060
a theorem or another lemma.

00:52:27.060 --> 00:52:29.970
In fact, now we're going to
get to the theorem, which

00:52:29.970 --> 00:52:32.820
is sort of the final thing--
the thing we're really after.

00:52:32.820 --> 00:52:34.315
And that's sort of the big deal.

00:52:34.315 --> 00:52:35.690
And now the proof
will be simple,

00:52:35.690 --> 00:52:38.512
because we've done all these
lemmas and corollaries.

00:52:38.512 --> 00:52:39.345
Any other questions?

00:52:42.230 --> 00:52:44.840
All right.

00:52:44.840 --> 00:52:49.170
In fact, the theorem
is up here, right?

00:52:49.170 --> 00:52:52.040
There is no sequence of legal
moves to invert g and h.

00:52:52.040 --> 00:52:53.950
In other words, the
students were screwed.

00:52:53.950 --> 00:52:57.060
They couldn't do it fairly.

00:52:57.060 --> 00:52:58.400
So let's prove the theorem now.

00:53:28.590 --> 00:53:39.030
The parity of the
number of inversions

00:53:39.030 --> 00:53:42.520
in the desired state-- i.e.

00:53:42.520 --> 00:53:51.050
in order-- the target
state-- is even.

00:53:51.050 --> 00:53:52.160
Nothing's out of order.

00:53:52.160 --> 00:53:55.320
There's zero inversions.

00:53:55.320 --> 00:54:07.030
By Lemma Four, the desired
state cannot be reached from

00:54:07.030 --> 00:54:26.450
the start state, because
its parity is odd,

00:54:26.450 --> 00:54:27.750
using legal moves.

00:54:27.750 --> 00:54:28.420
So we're done.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:30.290
So the proof of the
theorem-- by now,

00:54:30.290 --> 00:54:34.200
it's short, because we did four
lemmas, a corollary, and lots

00:54:34.200 --> 00:54:34.790
of argument.

00:54:38.850 --> 00:54:43.010
Could you have solved the puzzle
if I allow the blank to be

00:54:43.010 --> 00:54:46.680
somewhere else at the end?

00:54:46.680 --> 00:54:48.250
Is the puzzle solvable then?

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:52.250
No.

00:54:52.250 --> 00:54:52.790
Why not?

00:54:55.770 --> 00:54:58.105
Doesn't impact the parity at
all, so you can't do that.

00:55:04.450 --> 00:55:06.300
Again, the idea
here-- and you'll

00:55:06.300 --> 00:55:08.850
get some practice
in homework-- is

00:55:08.850 --> 00:55:12.140
you're looking for a property
that holds at the beginning,

00:55:12.140 --> 00:55:15.400
is preserved by every
step, but is not

00:55:15.400 --> 00:55:19.190
present in the target state.

00:55:19.190 --> 00:55:22.980
Now actually, this puzzle
was enormously popular

00:55:22.980 --> 00:55:25.260
in the late 1880s.

00:55:25.260 --> 00:55:29.260
In fact there was $1,000
prize offered for anybody

00:55:29.260 --> 00:55:31.640
who could solve
the larger version.

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:34.310
Back then, it was the 15
puzzle, which you can still

00:55:34.310 --> 00:55:37.740
buy today-- same problem
on a 4 by 4 grid--

00:55:37.740 --> 00:55:39.150
exactly the same problem.

00:55:39.150 --> 00:55:40.470
A pair is out of order.

00:55:40.470 --> 00:55:42.430
You've got to get them in order.

00:55:42.430 --> 00:55:44.510
You can't do it.

00:55:44.510 --> 00:55:46.460
Now, the proof
you can't do it is

00:55:46.460 --> 00:55:50.210
a little harder-- same
idea-- one extra idea

00:55:50.210 --> 00:55:52.570
in it-- one extra lemma.

00:55:52.570 --> 00:55:54.080
And that's for homework.

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:56.700
So you'll go through and
see exactly the structure

00:55:56.700 --> 00:55:59.360
with one extra little trick it.

00:55:59.360 --> 00:56:02.177
But back then, I guess most
people didn't-- of course,

00:56:02.177 --> 00:56:04.010
most people didn't
realize it wasn't doable.

00:56:04.010 --> 00:56:06.250
So they could offer
this price safely.

00:56:06.250 --> 00:56:11.130
$1,000 then is probably worth a
quarter million dollars today.

00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:13.440
Any questions on
the eight puzzle?

00:56:13.440 --> 00:56:15.624
Yeah.

00:56:15.624 --> 00:56:19.261
AUDIENCE: The
inductive steps-- when

00:56:19.261 --> 00:56:23.064
you said, "by inductive
hypothesis," [INAUDIBLE] parity

00:56:23.064 --> 00:56:27.465
after, shouldn't the
first term be M0?

00:56:27.465 --> 00:56:28.340
PROFESSOR: Let's see.

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:31.250
No, the first move is M1.

00:56:31.250 --> 00:56:33.410
The second is M2.

00:56:33.410 --> 00:56:36.859
Now, when I talk
about zero moves,

00:56:36.859 --> 00:56:38.400
that means no moves
are taking place.

00:56:38.400 --> 00:56:39.970
I'm still in the start state.

00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:42.920
So a move is a transition
between states.

00:56:42.920 --> 00:56:44.160
So you could have state 0.

00:56:44.160 --> 00:56:45.556
That's the start state.

00:56:45.556 --> 00:56:49.685
State one would be the
move after move one.

00:56:49.685 --> 00:56:50.810
Have I got that right here?

00:56:50.810 --> 00:56:56.550
So the inductive step, I need
to show P0 zero implies P1.

00:56:56.550 --> 00:56:59.070
P1 implies P2, and so forth.

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:03.620
And P n is the parity of
inversions after n moves.

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:07.670
So you could have state s0.

00:57:07.670 --> 00:57:12.835
We didn't label the states here,
but you could have state s0.

00:57:12.835 --> 00:57:13.817
Yeah.

00:57:13.817 --> 00:57:17.499
AUDIENCE: So in this problem,
we assume that everything should

00:57:17.499 --> 00:57:20.830
be defined as rows or columns.

00:57:20.830 --> 00:57:25.454
How do we know when the
assumptions are valid?

00:57:25.454 --> 00:57:26.870
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

00:57:26.870 --> 00:57:31.071
OK, so really,
there's two cases.

00:57:31.071 --> 00:57:32.570
To be really precise,
we should have

00:57:32.570 --> 00:57:35.510
argued there's only two types of
moves, a row move and a column

00:57:35.510 --> 00:57:36.037
move.

00:57:36.037 --> 00:57:38.620
And in fact, if you look at what
can move into a blank square,

00:57:38.620 --> 00:57:40.919
there's four guys that
can do it-- the guy above,

00:57:40.919 --> 00:57:43.460
the guy to the right, the guy
to the left, and the guy below.

00:57:43.460 --> 00:57:45.549
Two of those are row
moves, two are columns.

00:57:45.549 --> 00:57:47.590
So that's right-- to really
pin down the details,

00:57:47.590 --> 00:57:50.696
we should have checked those
are the only two possible moves.

00:57:50.696 --> 00:57:53.320
And if there was a third kind of
move that I hadn't considered,

00:57:53.320 --> 00:57:55.860
this proof would be bogus.

00:57:55.860 --> 00:57:58.290
That's a good question.

00:57:58.290 --> 00:57:59.141
Any other questions?

00:58:02.230 --> 00:58:04.880
OK.

00:58:04.880 --> 00:58:07.142
Now, I think
probably, you see why

00:58:07.142 --> 00:58:08.350
the invariants are important.

00:58:08.350 --> 00:58:12.290
But say that someday,
you're building software

00:58:12.290 --> 00:58:14.762
to run a nuclear reactor.

00:58:14.762 --> 00:58:16.470
Now, there's a certain
state you'd really

00:58:16.470 --> 00:58:19.530
like to avoid-- meltdown.

00:58:19.530 --> 00:58:21.310
And you'd like to
be able to prove

00:58:21.310 --> 00:58:25.220
that, in any sequence of moves
that happen in your reactor

00:58:25.220 --> 00:58:28.800
program, you never reach
the meltdown state.

00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:31.160
Well you'd use
invariants to do that.

00:58:31.160 --> 00:58:34.950
Or if you're building
software for an airplane,

00:58:34.950 --> 00:58:37.400
you'd like to never
reach the crash state.

00:58:37.400 --> 00:58:39.860
Or if you're building
a radiation device,

00:58:39.860 --> 00:58:44.330
you never want to get in the
state that fries the patient.

00:58:44.330 --> 00:58:48.425
So this is an important notion.

00:58:48.425 --> 00:58:49.800
So for the rest
of the day, we're

00:58:49.800 --> 00:58:52.470
going to talk about a
different kind of induction

00:58:52.470 --> 00:58:55.390
called strong induction.

00:58:55.390 --> 00:58:58.020
It's very similar to
ordinary induction,

00:58:58.020 --> 00:59:02.970
but it's a little easier to use
when solving certain problems.

00:59:02.970 --> 00:59:05.820
Now like regular
induction, strong induction

00:59:05.820 --> 00:59:07.908
can be expressed with an axiom.

00:59:12.490 --> 00:59:14.594
So let me show you the
strong induction axiom.

00:59:44.420 --> 00:59:46.420
You have a predicate,
P n, like before.

00:59:54.570 --> 01:00:04.840
If P0 is true-- your base
case-- and for all n,

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:10.330
it's not P n implies P
n plus 1, it's P0 and P1

01:00:10.330 --> 01:00:19.430
and dot, dot, dot, and P n
are all true, then P n plus 1.

01:00:19.430 --> 01:00:29.242
If this is true for all n,
then P n is true for all n.

01:00:38.410 --> 01:00:41.470
Now, the only difference
between strong induction

01:00:41.470 --> 01:00:46.380
and ordinary induction that
we did last time is this part.

01:00:49.460 --> 01:00:52.220
In ordinary induction,
you're showing

01:00:52.220 --> 01:00:54.830
that P n implies P n plus 1.

01:00:54.830 --> 01:00:58.360
In strong induction, you're
showing that all these facts

01:00:58.360 --> 01:01:02.880
put together imply P n plus 1.

01:01:02.880 --> 01:01:04.810
Now, to show
implication, remember,

01:01:04.810 --> 01:01:08.234
you get to assume that
all these things are true.

01:01:08.234 --> 01:01:10.150
So you know how in
ordinary induction, we say,

01:01:10.150 --> 01:01:13.890
"assume P n is true and you're
going to prove P n plus 1?"

01:01:13.890 --> 01:01:17.440
In strong induction, you get
to say, "assume P n is true,

01:01:17.440 --> 01:01:20.070
P n minus 1 is true, dot,
dot, dot, P1 is true,

01:01:20.070 --> 01:01:21.840
and P0 is true.

01:01:21.840 --> 01:01:24.650
You get to assume a lot more.

01:01:24.650 --> 01:01:26.810
So it's a stronger
proof technique,

01:01:26.810 --> 01:01:30.520
because it allows you to do
more-- or so you would think.

01:01:30.520 --> 01:01:34.162
Now in fact, any proof you
can do with strong induction,

01:01:34.162 --> 01:01:35.620
you can do with
ordinary induction.

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:36.990
It just might be harder.

01:01:36.990 --> 01:01:38.600
So you can't prove
any more with it,

01:01:38.600 --> 01:01:40.300
but it makes your
proofs much easier.

01:01:40.300 --> 01:01:42.133
And we're going to do
an example in a minute

01:01:42.133 --> 01:01:44.320
where the proof is
much easier by getting

01:01:44.320 --> 01:01:47.330
to assume all of these
things are true in order

01:01:47.330 --> 01:01:50.880
to prove P n plus 1.

01:01:50.880 --> 01:01:53.990
Are there any questions
about the difference here

01:01:53.990 --> 01:01:57.150
with strong induction-- that
now you get to assume all these

01:01:57.150 --> 01:02:01.910
are true as part of
the inductive step?

01:02:01.910 --> 01:02:02.410
All right.

01:02:04.930 --> 01:02:07.410
Our first example of
a strong induction

01:02:07.410 --> 01:02:10.210
is going to be a simple game.

01:02:10.210 --> 01:02:13.380
We've got a stack of
eight blocks here.

01:02:13.380 --> 01:02:15.680
Now, in this game,
what you're going to do

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:21.490
is divide the stack
into two sub-stacks.

01:02:21.490 --> 01:02:25.470
So I just took eight, and
split it into three and five.

01:02:25.470 --> 01:02:30.390
For that move, you get
15 points-- 3 times 5.

01:02:30.390 --> 01:02:31.490
Let's write that down.

01:02:45.370 --> 01:02:47.450
OK, so this is called
the Unstacking Game.

01:02:54.810 --> 01:03:02.140
And in the first move, we
went 8 split to 5 and 3.

01:03:02.140 --> 01:03:03.940
And that's worth 15 points.

01:03:06.850 --> 01:03:12.100
Now in the next move, I'm going
to split the stack of five

01:03:12.100 --> 01:03:14.160
into four and one.

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:16.760
And for that, you get
4 points-- 4 times 1.

01:03:21.230 --> 01:03:26.610
And I keep on going until I
have a stacks of height one.

01:03:26.610 --> 01:03:29.270
And the last move, I'll be
splitting a two into two ones.

01:03:29.270 --> 01:03:30.810
That'll give me one point.

01:03:30.810 --> 01:03:35.080
Then I add up all the points,
and that's your score.

01:03:35.080 --> 01:03:38.630
And the goal is to get
the most number of points

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:41.200
when you add up
the entire score.

01:03:41.200 --> 01:03:45.730
Now, just so this game is
clear, we're going to play it.

01:03:45.730 --> 01:03:48.049
And I'm going to
raise the stakes here.

01:03:48.049 --> 01:03:49.590
What we're going to
do is we're going

01:03:49.590 --> 01:03:51.980
to have a competition
between three members

01:03:51.980 --> 01:03:55.610
of the class and the TAs.

01:03:55.610 --> 01:04:00.020
Now, if the class team
wins-- they get more points--

01:04:00.020 --> 01:04:02.720
we're going to give
everybody in the class candy.

01:04:02.720 --> 01:04:06.340
And I've got lots of candy here.

01:04:06.340 --> 01:04:09.668
If the TAs beat you,
they get the candy.

01:04:09.668 --> 01:04:11.610
AUDIENCE: What if it's a tie?

01:04:11.610 --> 01:04:13.679
PROFESSOR: We'll
figure that out.

01:04:13.679 --> 01:04:14.720
We'll come to that later.

01:04:14.720 --> 01:04:16.140
But you want to win this thing.

01:04:16.140 --> 01:04:18.216
So I need some
volunteers from the class

01:04:18.216 --> 01:04:19.340
who think they can do well.

01:04:19.340 --> 01:04:21.030
Yeah, come on down.

01:04:21.030 --> 01:04:23.740
You two guys come on down.

01:04:23.740 --> 01:04:25.000
All right, TAs come on up.

01:04:30.030 --> 01:04:31.760
Now, I want you
to make some noise

01:04:31.760 --> 01:04:35.796
if you think your three class
reps here can beat the TAs.

01:04:35.796 --> 01:04:38.102
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

01:04:38.102 --> 01:04:40.970
All right, how many
people-- make some noise you

01:04:40.970 --> 01:04:42.540
think the TAs are going to win.

01:04:42.540 --> 01:04:43.212
AUDIENCE: Ooh.

01:04:43.212 --> 01:04:44.420
PROFESSOR: Ooh, that's nasty.

01:04:44.420 --> 01:04:47.180
It must've been a rough
recitation last week

01:04:47.180 --> 01:04:48.930
on Wednesday.

01:04:48.930 --> 01:04:50.884
All right, so let's see.

01:04:50.884 --> 01:04:52.800
I think we're going to
let the class go first.

01:04:52.800 --> 01:04:54.160
This is your stack.

01:04:54.160 --> 01:04:56.270
Now think about what move
you want to make first,

01:04:56.270 --> 01:04:57.750
because that matters.

01:04:57.750 --> 01:05:00.630
And you guys can give them
some advice if you want,

01:05:00.630 --> 01:05:02.887
as to the move they
should make first.

01:05:02.887 --> 01:05:04.470
And I'm going to
keep score over here.

01:05:08.820 --> 01:05:11.070
Oh, OK, they went
for the maximum move.

01:05:11.070 --> 01:05:11.580
That's good.

01:05:11.580 --> 01:05:16.160
They realized 4 times
4 is 16-- very good.

01:05:16.160 --> 01:05:19.705
So let's write that up here.

01:05:19.705 --> 01:05:23.380
You're Off to a good start.

01:05:23.380 --> 01:05:25.370
In fact, that's the
maximum number of points

01:05:25.370 --> 01:05:28.720
for the first move,
I think-- good job.

01:05:32.320 --> 01:05:36.490
All right, so here's
the class here.

01:05:36.490 --> 01:05:37.640
And here are the TAs.

01:05:40.620 --> 01:05:48.135
And the class went 8 into
4 by 4, and they got 16.

01:05:51.030 --> 01:05:55.340
Now, the TAs are working
hard here, as you can see.

01:05:55.340 --> 01:05:56.890
And they've got a move.

01:05:56.890 --> 01:05:59.910
That's a pretty pathetic
first move for the TAs.

01:05:59.910 --> 01:06:03.230
Looking good for the
candy for you guys.

01:06:03.230 --> 01:06:06.980
They got 7 points for the TAs.

01:06:06.980 --> 01:06:09.672
Class, what would you like
to do for your next move?

01:06:09.672 --> 01:06:10.588
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:06:16.220 --> 01:06:19.274
PROFESSOR: You can't start
over now-- too late for that.

01:06:19.274 --> 01:06:22.000
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:24.140
A lot of people
counting on you guys.

01:06:24.140 --> 01:06:27.830
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:06:27.830 --> 01:06:29.480
Oh, no, no, one at a time.

01:06:29.480 --> 01:06:30.990
No, just one.

01:06:30.990 --> 01:06:33.866
One stack gets
split-- either one.

01:06:33.866 --> 01:06:35.540
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:06:35.540 --> 01:06:37.200
PROFESSOR: There you go.

01:06:37.200 --> 01:06:39.668
Oh, well, what do you do now?

01:06:39.668 --> 01:06:42.656
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:06:42.656 --> 01:06:45.146
AUDIENCE: Their strategy's
obviously better than ours.

01:06:45.146 --> 01:06:46.142
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but we've
figured it out already.

01:06:46.142 --> 01:06:46.640
AUDIENCE: We're going to lose.

01:06:46.640 --> 01:06:48.931
PROFESSOR: The TAs are
convinced they're going to lose.

01:06:48.931 --> 01:06:52.279
Three and one, OK,
good, interesting.

01:06:52.279 --> 01:06:53.320
So we have three and one.

01:06:53.320 --> 01:06:56.110
That gives you 3 points.

01:06:56.110 --> 01:06:58.000
All right, TAs, we need a move.

01:07:02.090 --> 01:07:08.000
All right, so they've gone
six and one-- 6 points.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:13.330
Class, you think
you're dead already?

01:07:13.330 --> 01:07:17.130
So you've gotten three
and one now, again, for 3.

01:07:17.130 --> 01:07:18.160
So you're up to 22.

01:07:18.160 --> 01:07:20.570
You're way ahead-- 22 to 13.

01:07:20.570 --> 01:07:23.307
All right, TAs.

01:07:23.307 --> 01:07:24.890
They look a little
disorganized to me.

01:07:24.890 --> 01:07:25.694
What do you think?

01:07:25.694 --> 01:07:26.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:29.190 --> 01:07:31.315
PROFESSOR: Another one--
you can tell where they're

01:07:31.315 --> 01:07:32.970
headed here-- five and one.

01:07:32.970 --> 01:07:33.792
They have 5 points.

01:07:33.792 --> 01:07:34.500
They're up to 18.

01:07:34.500 --> 01:07:37.300
They're 4 behind you.

01:07:37.300 --> 01:07:39.146
All right, class.

01:07:39.146 --> 01:07:43.640
All right, you got 2 points.

01:07:43.640 --> 01:07:53.290
TAs-- you really think they
know how to do this best?

01:07:53.290 --> 01:07:53.854
I don't know.

01:07:53.854 --> 01:07:54.770
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:02.380 --> 01:08:04.890
PROFESSOR: Oh, big
change in strategy there.

01:08:08.500 --> 01:08:10.520
All that thinking, and
that's what we got.

01:08:10.520 --> 01:08:13.371
OK, 4 points.

01:08:13.371 --> 01:08:13.870
Class.

01:08:20.029 --> 01:08:22.939
