01:12:59.170 --> 01:13:01.340
OK, so while you're
doing that, let's

01:13:01.340 --> 01:13:02.590
try to prove this theorem.

01:13:16.130 --> 01:13:21.830
So the theorem is that all
strategies for the n-block game

01:13:21.830 --> 01:13:25.460
produce the same score.

01:13:25.460 --> 01:13:26.765
It wasn't a coincidence for 8.

01:13:31.900 --> 01:13:36.070
And the score, we'll call it
S of n for the n-block game.

01:13:36.070 --> 01:13:41.420
So for example, we're trying
to show that S of 8 was 28.

01:13:45.760 --> 01:13:47.380
So what strategy
do you think we're

01:13:47.380 --> 01:13:48.505
going to use for the proof?

01:13:49.146 --> 01:13:50.270
AUDIENCE: Strong induction.

01:13:50.270 --> 01:13:51.784
PROFESSOR: Strong
induction-- so you

01:13:51.784 --> 01:13:53.950
want to write that down--
proof by strong induction.

01:14:02.110 --> 01:14:07.430
What's the next step in a
proof by any kind of induction?

01:14:07.430 --> 01:14:08.650
AUDIENCE: Base case.

01:14:08.650 --> 01:14:11.230
PROFESSOR: Base case-- not yet.

01:14:11.230 --> 01:14:12.230
AUDIENCE: The predicate.

01:14:12.230 --> 01:14:15.880
PROFESSOR: The predicate--
what's the predicate here?

01:14:15.880 --> 01:14:19.460
All right, so for the
inductive hypothesis,

01:14:19.460 --> 01:14:24.118
the predicate-- any guesses as
to what P of n is going to be?

01:14:24.118 --> 01:14:26.330
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:26.330 --> 01:14:27.288
PROFESSOR: What's that?

01:14:27.288 --> 01:14:31.070
AUDIENCE: n should
be 2n minus 1 by 2.

01:14:31.070 --> 01:14:33.280
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
that's part of it,

01:14:33.280 --> 01:14:36.680
but we're going to use this
as a predicate to start with.

01:14:36.680 --> 01:14:38.882
You've gone a step ahead there.

01:14:38.882 --> 01:14:41.090
So I'm going to start with
this as being a predicate,

01:14:41.090 --> 01:14:43.150
because I'm trying to
show they're all the same.

01:14:43.150 --> 01:14:45.400
And I haven't figured out
what the scores going to be.

01:14:45.400 --> 01:14:47.970
But I think you're already
on a good track here for what

01:14:47.970 --> 01:14:50.410
the score is going to be.

01:14:50.410 --> 01:14:51.948
Now we do the base case.

01:14:58.430 --> 01:15:02.770
So we take n equals
1-- the one-block game.

01:15:02.770 --> 01:15:05.130
S of 1 is 0.

01:15:05.130 --> 01:15:06.170
We never took a move.

01:15:06.170 --> 01:15:07.080
We never got a score.

01:15:07.080 --> 01:15:08.150
There was only one block.

01:15:08.150 --> 01:15:10.560
We ended before we started.

01:15:10.560 --> 01:15:13.680
So that's OK.

01:15:13.680 --> 01:15:15.235
And now we have
the inductive step.

01:15:18.660 --> 01:15:29.510
And here we get to assume P1,
P2, all the way up to P n,

01:15:29.510 --> 01:15:31.610
to prove P n plus 1.

01:15:36.020 --> 01:15:41.791
And so now we look
at n plus 1 blocks,

01:15:41.791 --> 01:15:43.040
because that's we're starting.

01:15:48.210 --> 01:15:51.890
So we have n plus 1,
and we split it somehow.

01:15:51.890 --> 01:15:53.500
And it could be any split.

01:15:53.500 --> 01:15:57.700
We might have K on one
side, then n plus 1 minus K

01:15:57.700 --> 01:16:01.727
on the other side for
any K between 1 and n.

01:16:05.630 --> 01:16:08.660
And let's figure out our
score for that scenario.

01:16:12.600 --> 01:16:15.170
Well, we get the
product of these numbers

01:16:15.170 --> 01:16:18.060
for the first step.

01:16:18.060 --> 01:16:24.100
We get K times n plus 1
minus K for the first step.

01:16:24.100 --> 01:16:27.750
And then as we recurse,
and we split up

01:16:27.750 --> 01:16:31.300
that block of K blocks,
how many points do we

01:16:31.300 --> 01:16:34.030
get for splitting
that all the way down?

01:16:34.030 --> 01:16:34.900
AUDIENCE: P of K.

01:16:34.900 --> 01:16:37.191
PROFESSOR: P of K, because
that's the induction.

01:16:37.191 --> 01:16:39.315
We assume that as part of
the induction hypothesis.

01:16:42.700 --> 01:16:45.080
And how many points do
we get for splitting

01:16:45.080 --> 01:16:46.260
this stack all the way down?

01:16:48.940 --> 01:16:55.590
Yeah, P of n plus 1 minus K.

01:16:55.590 --> 01:16:57.330
And you see why
strong induction's

01:16:57.330 --> 01:17:00.310
coming in handy here?

01:17:00.310 --> 01:17:02.990
For the TA's strategy,
K would be 1.

01:17:02.990 --> 01:17:05.099
We know P of 1 is 0.

01:17:05.099 --> 01:17:06.890
And you would just need
ordinary induction.

01:17:06.890 --> 01:17:08.760
This would be P of n.

01:17:08.760 --> 01:17:11.300
But for a general strategy,
it could be any split.

01:17:11.300 --> 01:17:13.110
So we need to have all
these assumed here.

01:17:13.110 --> 01:17:18.330
It makes it much easier
when using strong induction.

01:17:18.330 --> 01:17:20.310
All right, so this
is our total score

01:17:20.310 --> 01:17:23.180
for the game for
n plus 1 blocks.

01:17:23.180 --> 01:17:28.240
And we're trying to show
it just depends on n,

01:17:28.240 --> 01:17:33.149
and that it doesn't depend
on K. Does that depend on K?

01:17:38.030 --> 01:17:40.210
Looks like it to me, right?

01:17:40.210 --> 01:17:44.020
I got K in every single term.

01:17:44.020 --> 01:17:44.740
So I'm not there.

01:17:44.740 --> 01:17:45.240
I'm stuck.

01:17:47.720 --> 01:17:48.939
You see why I'm stuck?

01:17:48.939 --> 01:17:51.230
Because I'd like to be able
to say that the score I get

01:17:51.230 --> 01:17:54.120
for the n plus one
block game-- this

01:17:54.120 --> 01:17:58.520
is S n plus 1-- is the same
for any sequence of moves.

01:17:58.520 --> 01:18:02.260
It doesn't even depend on
K. But I can't do that.

01:18:02.260 --> 01:18:05.310
What do you do when you're
stuck with an induction proof?

01:18:05.310 --> 01:18:06.460
What's one of the tricks?

01:18:06.460 --> 01:18:07.584
AUDIENCE: Make it stronger.

01:18:07.584 --> 01:18:09.800
PROFESSOR: Make
it stronger, which

01:18:09.800 --> 01:18:13.360
means I get a stronger
induction hypothesis.

01:18:13.360 --> 01:18:17.030
Now, somebody gave me
one up there before.

01:18:17.030 --> 01:18:19.196
How could I strengthen my
induction hypothesis here?

01:18:22.052 --> 01:18:23.960
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:18:23.960 --> 01:18:27.320
PROFESSOR: Give the
formula for S n-- that

01:18:27.320 --> 01:18:28.360
would make it stronger.

01:18:28.360 --> 01:18:30.140
I tell you what it is.

01:18:30.140 --> 01:18:32.760
What's a good guess
for the formula here?

01:18:32.760 --> 01:18:33.700
AUDIENCE: Factorial.

01:18:33.700 --> 01:18:41.580
PROFESSOR: Factorial-- Well,
is S of 8 equal 8 factorial?

01:18:41.580 --> 01:18:44.234
No, not so good.

01:18:44.234 --> 01:18:46.631
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:18:46.631 --> 01:18:48.130
AUDIENCE: n equals
n minus 1 over 2.

01:18:48.130 --> 01:18:51.510
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
that's a better guess--

01:18:51.510 --> 01:18:56.160
equals n times n minus 1 over 2.

01:18:56.160 --> 01:18:59.750
And in fact, what's
8 times 7 over 2?

01:18:59.750 --> 01:19:00.330
It's 28.

01:19:00.330 --> 01:19:01.770
It works here.

01:19:01.770 --> 01:19:02.770
Let's check another one.

01:19:02.770 --> 01:19:04.520
What's S of 2?

01:19:07.171 --> 01:19:07.670
AUDIENCE: 1.

01:19:07.670 --> 01:19:12.740
PROFESSOR: 1-- well, 2
times 1 over 2-- it works.

01:19:12.740 --> 01:19:14.690
What's S of 3?

01:19:17.600 --> 01:19:21.130
2 the first move, then 1 more.

01:19:21.130 --> 01:19:26.340
3-- 3 times 2 over
2 is 3-- looks good.

01:19:26.340 --> 01:19:28.430
So now I've got a stronger
induction hypothesis.

01:19:28.430 --> 01:19:30.220
Not only is it
always the same, it

01:19:30.220 --> 01:19:33.710
is that number is your score.

01:19:33.710 --> 01:19:35.190
Let's see if that works.

01:19:35.190 --> 01:19:38.000
Let's plug that in now.

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:40.560
So base case--
let's check it out--

01:19:40.560 --> 01:19:47.520
is 1 times 1 minus
1 over 2 equal to 0.

01:19:47.520 --> 01:19:49.750
Yes.

01:19:49.750 --> 01:19:53.040
Let's plug it in here now.

01:19:53.040 --> 01:19:58.570
P of K would be now
K, K minus 1 over 2.

01:19:58.570 --> 01:20:08.220
This would be n plus 1 minus K,
n minus K over 2 plus this one

01:20:08.220 --> 01:20:08.720
here.

01:20:12.140 --> 01:20:15.850
All right, I've got to add
all these things up, and see

01:20:15.850 --> 01:20:19.473
if it equals that
expression for n plus 1.

01:20:19.473 --> 01:20:20.435
Let's do that.

01:20:23.330 --> 01:20:29.780
All right, I get 2 K n
plus 2 K minus 2 K squared.

01:20:29.780 --> 01:20:34.920
I'm putting all this over 2--
one giant mess over 2 here--

01:20:34.920 --> 01:20:43.120
plus K squared minus
K plus n squared.

01:20:43.120 --> 01:20:52.940
Well, let's write it just as
n plus 1 times n, minus K n,

01:20:52.940 --> 01:20:57.860
minus K, minus K n, all over 2.

01:20:57.860 --> 01:20:59.770
And now let's cancel.

01:20:59.770 --> 01:21:04.420
Two K n's here cancel K n, K n.

01:21:04.420 --> 01:21:12.310
2K cancels K and K. 2K
squared minus 2 K squared

01:21:12.310 --> 01:21:14.070
cancels K squared.

01:21:14.070 --> 01:21:20.970
And I forgot, plus K
squared from here and here.

01:21:20.970 --> 01:21:25.040
So I'm left with n
plus 1 times n over 2.

01:21:25.040 --> 01:21:26.450
That is S n plus 1.

01:21:29.080 --> 01:21:30.770
And the K disappears.

01:21:30.770 --> 01:21:34.740
We've established, now, the
stronger induction hypothesis.

01:21:34.740 --> 01:21:38.980
So not only did we prove
that every set of unstackings

01:21:38.980 --> 01:21:40.960
gives you the same score.

01:21:40.960 --> 01:21:46.010
We proved the score is, for
n blocks, n times n minus 1

01:21:46.010 --> 01:21:46.570
over 2.

01:21:49.787 --> 01:21:51.620
That's was pretty good
for strong induction.

01:21:51.620 --> 01:21:53.710
It lets you do some
pretty powerful things.

01:21:53.710 --> 01:21:56.820
OK, very good,
that's it for today.

